---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { GROUPS, CONCEPTS, conceptById } from "../data/concepts.mjs";
import fundamentals from "../data/fundamentals.json";
import { roicValue, ownerEarningsMargin, liquidAssets, cashConversionCycle, debtReliable, topLineRevenue } from "../lib/fundamentals.mjs";
import { financialKind, classify } from "../lib/archetype.mjs";

// One learning hub: first the method — how to read a business, start to finish, in the order an owner
// asks the questions — then the vocabulary, every term defined once. The method pronounces no verdict
// and names no stock; the whole point is to hand the reader the questions, not the answers. Static
// prose, nothing computed. The /concepts URL is preserved because every company page links into its
// #term anchors; the method sits above them, and #vocabulary jumps straight to the glossary.
const byGroup = (key) => CONCEPTS.filter((c) => c.group === key);

// Bridge each measurable idea to reality: the catalog companies where it shows up most plainly, so a
// reader can leave the definition and go watch it at work. Same sourced figures, recognizable names
// only (a revenue floor), never a recommendation, just where the number runs high (or, for dilution,
// where it runs the wrong way).
const big = (fundamentals.companies || []).filter((c) => (topLineRevenue(c.lines, c) || 0) > 3e9);
const ind = big.filter((c) => !financialKind(c));
const median = (xs) => { const s = [...xs].sort((a, b) => a - b); return s.length ? s[Math.floor((s.length - 1) / 2)] : null; };
const medianRoic = (c) => { const v = (c.history || []).map((h) => roicValue(h.lines)).filter((x) => x != null); return v.length >= 4 ? median(v) : null; };
const grossM = (c) => { const L = c.lines || {}; return L.revenue && L.costOfRevenue != null ? 1 - L.costOfRevenue / L.revenue : null; };
const netCashOf = (c) => { const L = c.lines || {}; return debtReliable(L) ? (liquidAssets(L) || 0) - (L.totalDebt || 0) : null; };
const topBy = (pool, metric, n = 6, asc = false) =>
  pool.map((c) => ({ t: c.ticker, v: metric(c) })).filter((x) => x.v != null).sort((a, b) => (asc ? a.v - b.v : b.v - a.v)).slice(0, n).map((x) => x.t);
const brandLike = ind.filter((c) => ["consumer", "assetLight"].includes(classify(c).sector.key));
const EXEMPLARS = {
  roic: { label: "Returns that have held highest across the record", tickers: topBy(ind, medianRoic) },
  "owner-earnings": { label: "Most cash reaching owners", tickers: topBy(ind, (c) => ownerEarningsMargin(c.lines, c)) },
  "gross-margin": { label: "Widest gross margins (brands and asset-light)", tickers: topBy(brandLike, grossM) },
  "net-debt": { label: "Deepest net-cash balance sheets", tickers: topBy(ind, netCashOf) },
  "cash-conversion-cycle": { label: "Funded by customers and suppliers", tickers: big.filter((c) => cashConversionCycle(c)?.tone === "good").sort((a, b) => (topLineRevenue(b.lines, b) || 0) - (topLineRevenue(a.lines, a) || 0)).slice(0, 6).map((c) => c.ticker) },
};
---

<BaseLayout title="Principles, Owner Scorecard">
  <header class="hero">
    <h1>Principles</h1>
    <p class="dek">
      Reading a business, and owning one well — the order an owner works through a filing, the two roads
      the masters walked between a cheap bargain and a great franchise, and the vocabulary it all runs on.
      Drawn from Graham, Buffett and Munger; it hands you the questions and leaves the verdict yours.
    </p>
  </header>

  <section class="band">
    <div class="prose">
      <p>
        Graham taught that an investment operation is one which, on thorough analysis, promises safety of
        principal and an adequate return — and that everything else is speculation. Buffett added the part
        that makes it doable: you do not have to study every business, only stay inside the few you can
        understand, and there judge them as an owner would, on the cash they will hand their owners over
        time. Munger supplied the discipline that protects you from yourself — invert, look for the ways
        it fails, and pass on anything you cannot hold in your head.
      </p>
      <p>
        None of that requires a terminal, a model, or a forecast. It requires reading the filing in a
        sensible order and being honest about what you find. The pages here lay that reading out for you,
        every figure traced to the company's own SEC filings, and they stop where judgment begins: they
        present the evidence and never tell you the answer. The answer is yours to form. What follows is
        how to form it — five questions, in the order an owner asks them. Read along on a real one as you
        go: <a href="/c/KO">open Coca-Cola</a> and find each part as it comes up.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="band">
    <h2>1 · What is it?</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>
        Start where an owner starts, not where a trader starts. Before a single ratio: what does this
        company sell, to whom, and how does it turn that into money? If you cannot say it in a plain
        sentence — the way you would explain it to someone at dinner — you do not yet understand it well
        enough to own it, and no amount of arithmetic will rescue you. Buffett's filter has always been
        this simple and this strict: stay inside what you can explain.
      </p>
      <p>
        On the page this is <b>What it is</b> and <b>Where the money comes from</b>. Read them together.
        The first says, in a few sentences drawn from the filing, what the business does and what one or
        two things actually decide its fate. The second follows the money into its segments and
        geographies — and shows you the concentration, because a company that earns most of its profit
        from one product or one country is carrying a risk the headline revenue hides. A business you can
        describe and whose money you can trace is a business you can begin to judge. One you cannot is one
        to put back on the shelf.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="band">
    <h2>2 · Is it a good business?</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>
        Now the economics. A good business, in the sense that matters to an owner, is one that earns a
        high return on the capital tied up in it and can do so again next year without a fight. Buffett's
        test is whether a dollar retained in the business becomes more than a dollar of market value over
        time — and that only happens when the business earns well above its cost of capital. So you look
        at the return on capital across the whole record, not one year, and you look at how much of each
        sales dollar actually reaches owners as cash — <a href="#owner-earnings">owner earnings</a>,
        operating cash less the capital spending needed just to stand still.
      </p>
      <p>
        On the page this is <b>The record</b> — a decade in one table, meant to be read <i>down the rows,
        a single line across all its years</i>, not across one year's column — and the <b>Is it a good
        business?</b> and <b>Earnings power</b> reads beside it. Watch three things. Has the
        <a href="#roic">return on capital</a> stayed high through good years and bad? Does owner earnings
        track the reported profit, or do the two drift apart (a sign the profit is not turning into cash)?
        And is this year a fair one to judge by, or a peak or a trough — Graham's whole point in
        normalizing across a cycle. A wonderful business answers all three the same way for years on end.
        A mediocre one earns its keep only at the top of its cycle.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="band">
    <h2>3 · Will it last?</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>
        A high return invites competition the way honey invites bears. So the next question is the one
        Munger cared about most: is there a moat — some durable reason the returns will still be here in
        ten years — and can the business get through a bad decade without a forced sale or a wiped-out
        balance sheet? This is two questions, and the order matters. First survival, then durability.
        Graham's first rule was never to lose; only a business that lives gets to compound.
      </p>
      <p>
        On the page, survival is <b>Will it survive?</b> and <b>Current Position</b> — can it pay its
        interest, cover its near-term bills, get through a downturn without depending on the kindness of
        lenders. Durability is <b>Durability &amp; moat</b>, and notice how it is written: it names the
        moat as a <i>test to watch</i> — pricing power that should show in margins that hold under
        pressure, switching costs that should show in customers who stay — and never as a fact the company
        possesses. That restraint is deliberate. A moat asserted is a story; a moat that shows up in the
        numbers, year after year, is an asset. The page hands you the place to look; whether the evidence
        is there is your call.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="band">
    <h2>4 · Who is running it, and what do they do with the cash?</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>
        A good business can be ruined by what is done with its profits, and a fair one made richer. After
        the operating return, a management's most important job is capital allocation — what it does with
        the cash the business throws off: reinvest it, buy other companies, pay it out, or buy back its
        own shares. Buffett judges the buybacks especially closely, because a repurchase made cheap builds
        per-share value and one made dear quietly destroys it. And underneath all of it sits the question
        of candor: does management tell its owners the truth, in plain words, including the bad news?
      </p>
      <p>
        On the page this is <b>How is the cash used?</b>, <b>Management &amp; pay</b>, and the candor read
        of what the filing emphasizes and how it talks to owners. Watch whether retained earnings have
        actually produced growth in value, whether buybacks were made when the shares were cheap or only
        when flush, and whether the filing owns its problems or buries them in adjusted figures and
        cheerful adjectives. Munger's rule of thumb is worth keeping here: show me the incentive and I
        will show you the outcome.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="band">
    <h2>5 · Invert — then, only then, the price.</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>
        Before you let yourself like a business, turn it over. Munger's habit was to invert: do not ask
        how this succeeds, ask how it fails — what would have to go wrong, and how likely is it. The page
        does this for you in <b>Inverting the record</b>, reading the record for the cracks rather than
        the case. If the bad cases are survivable and unlikely, you have something. If one of them is a
        coin-flip that ends the company, no price is cheap enough.
      </p>
      <p>
        And the price comes <i>last</i>, on purpose. A great business at a foolish price is a poor
        investment; a fair one bought with a margin of safety is Graham's whole edifice. <b>The price</b>
        and <b>What the price implies</b> turn the reverse-DCF around: instead of pretending to forecast,
        they show you what growth the current price is already counting on, so you can ask whether the
        record makes that plausible or heroic. The
        <a href="#margin-of-safety">margin of safety</a> is the gap between what you pay and what the
        business is worth — and the wider it is, the less your judgment has to be right.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="band">
    <h2>A note · some businesses read differently</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>
        Most companies sell a thing and keep part of what comes in, and the five questions read them
        straight. But a few kinds run on a different engine, and forcing them through the ordinary gauges
        — gross margin, owner earnings, return on invested capital — tells you nothing, or worse, tells
        you something false. The pages know this and switch instruments; here is what changes, and why,
        for the three you will meet most. The questions do not change. Only the gauges do.
      </p>
      <p>
        <b>A bank</b> sells money, and money is a commodity, so a bank wins not on margin but on funding
        itself cheaply — sticky, low-cost deposits — and lending wisely. A bank <i>is</i> a balance
        sheet, so you read it on <a href="#return-on-equity">return on equity</a>, the efficiency of the
        operation, and how thin the equity is against the assets, not on a margin. And the danger hides: a
        bank looks most profitable in the year just before its bad loans surface, because the losses were
        always in the book, merely unreserved. Buffett's caution is the whole of it — leverage turns a
        small underwriting mistake into a large one — which is why you judge a bank across a full credit
        cycle, never one fair-weather year. <a href="/c/JPM">See it on JPMorgan</a>.
      </p>
      <p>
        <b>An insurer</b> takes premiums today and pays claims years later, and in between it holds the
        money. Buffett built Berkshire on what that money is: <i>float</i> — funds the insurer holds but
        does not own, free to invest for its own account until the claims come due. A great underwriter is
        <i>paid</i> to hold its float, taking in more in premiums than it pays out (a combined ratio under
        100), so the float is leverage that costs less than nothing and compounds in the book value; a
        poor one pays for the privilege. So you read an insurer on the combined ratio — underwriting
        profit or loss — and on the growth in book value the float makes possible, not on a margin.
        <a href="/c/PGR">See it on Progressive</a>.
      </p>
      <p>
        <b>A property trust</b> is the case where the accounting itself misleads: GAAP makes a REIT
        depreciate buildings that are often appreciating, so reported "earnings" understate the cash by a
        wide margin. The honest figure is <a href="#ffo">funds from operations</a> — cash earnings with
        that paper depreciation added back — read against what the trust pays out and the debt stacked
        behind the property. Net income is the wrong number here; FFO is the right one.
        <a href="/c/O">See it on Realty Income</a>.
      </p>
      <p>
        In every case the spirit is the same. Ask what the business actually does with money, find the
        gauge that measures it honestly, and distrust the one the accounting hands you when it flatters.
        That is the discipline behind every page: the right instrument for the business, and the reasons
        shown so you can check them.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="band">
    <h2>Two roads · the bargain and the franchise</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>
        There is a fork in this whole tradition, and it pays to know which road you are on — because the
        masters themselves walked both.
      </p>
      <p>
        Graham's road is the bargain. He cared less whether a business was wonderful than whether it was
        cheap: cheap against its assets, its earnings, its plain liquidation value, bought with the margin
        of safety in the <i>price itself</i> and held in a diversified basket. When a bargain rose to fair
        value he sold it and moved to the next, the way a bee works flower to flower. He did not need to
        foresee which companies would rule the next decade; he needed only a crowd of things priced below
        what they were obviously worth, and the patience to let the weighing machine catch up with the
        voting machine. The protection was the discount, and the discipline was to insist on a wide one.
      </p>
      <p>
        Buffett and Munger started on that road and then stepped off it. Munger's contribution, repeated
        for half a century, was that a great business at a fair price beats a fair business at a great
        price — that a durable franchise, left alone, compounds in a way no cigar butt ever can. Buffett
        came to call the old hunt exactly that: cigar butts, a discarded stub with one free puff left,
        satisfying once and gone. See's Candies taught him the other thing — that a business able to raise
        its prices without losing its customers is worth paying up for, because time is the friend of the
        wonderful business and the enemy of the mediocre. So they bought franchises and held them for
        decades, and let the math of compounding and a long American boom do the rest.
      </p>
      <p>
        Both roads are honest, and which is yours depends on what you are and where you stand. The
        franchise road rewards size, patience, and an era thick with great businesses to hold; it is the
        road of permanent capital. The bargain road rewards a small purse and a market full of overlooked,
        mispriced things — and here it is worth hearing Buffett plainly, as he has said more than once:
        were he running a small sum again he would not be buying the great compounders everyone can
        already see; he would be back in Graham's pond, turning over tiny, unloved bargains, and he
        believed he could compound at fifty percent a year doing it. The small investor's supposed
        handicap is, in this one respect, an edge — you can fish in waters too small for the giants, where
        the bargains still hide.
      </p>
      <p>
        So read the business the same way on either road; the five questions hold whichever hunt you are
        on. Only know which hunt it is. If your capital is small and your temperament is for turning over
        many rocks rather than sitting on a few, you may belong more on Graham's road than on Berkshire's
        — and you would be in the best of company, for it is where Buffett began, and where he has said he
        would begin again.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="band">
    <h2>The most important idea, saved for last · Mr. Market</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>
        Graham left one character for the end, and Buffett has called him the most valuable idea in all
        of investing. Imagine you own half of a business with a partner — call him Mr. Market — who is
        obliging to a fault: every single day he names a price at which he will either buy your half or
        sell you his. He is also, unfortunately, emotionally unstable. Some days he is euphoric and can
        see only the good ahead, so he names a wildly high price; other days he is despairing and will
        offer you his half for a pittance. And he does not mind being ignored — turn him down today and he
        is back tomorrow with a new quote.
      </p>
      <p>
        The point of the allegory is the whole point of this site. Mr. Market's prices are there to
        <i>serve</i> you, not to instruct you. A quote that has fallen is not a fact about the business;
        it is an offer, and an offer is only good news to someone who knows what the thing is worth. That
        is the entire reason to read a business the way these pages lay it out — so that when Mr. Market is
        fearful you are equipped to buy from him, when he is greedy you can sell to him, and the rest of
        the time you can let him shout and go back to reading. Graham's other warning belongs here too:
        the investor's chief problem, and even his worst enemy, is likely to be himself. The numbers are
        the easy part. The discipline to act on them, and only on them, is the part no page can do for you.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="band bridge">
    <div class="prose">
      <p>
        That is the whole of it: understand it, judge its economics, test that they will last, weigh its
        stewards, invert, and only then look at the price — five questions, on one business at a time. The
        words you will meet along the way are defined below; learn one and it travels with you to any
        filing you open, in this catalog or not. Then do as Buffett said and start with the
        <a href="/">A's</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="band intro" id="vocabulary">
    <h2>The vocabulary of ownership</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>
        The hard part of investing is not the arithmetic; it is knowing which few numbers matter and what
        each one is honestly telling you. Below is the handful of ideas the whole method runs on, from
        owner earnings to the margin of safety, each with the reasoning behind it and the place it can
        mislead you. None of it is secret, and none of it requires a terminal. Read the entry, then go
        watch the idea at work on a real company.
      </p>
    </div>
    <nav class="grpnav" aria-label="Sections">
      {GROUPS.map((g) => <a href={`#grp-${g.key}`}>{g.title}</a>)}
    </nav>
  </section>

  {GROUPS.map((g) => (
    <section class="band" id={`grp-${g.key}`}>
      <h2>{g.title}</h2>
      <p class="sub">{g.blurb}</p>
      <div class="concepts">
        {byGroup(g.key).map((c) => (
          <article class="concept" id={c.id}>
            <h3><a class="anchor" href={`#${c.id}`}>{c.term}</a></h3>
            <p class="short">{c.short}</p>
            <p class="cbody">{c.body}</p>
            {c.formula ? (
              <p class="formula"><span class="flabel">How it is figured</span>{c.formula}</p>
            ) : null}
            {c.forms && c.forms.length ? (
              <ul class="forms">
                <li class="formsHead">The same question, a different form in each business:</li>
                {c.forms.map((f) => (
                  <li><span class="formKind">{f.kind}</span> <span class="formRead">{f.read}</span></li>
                ))}
              </ul>
            ) : null}
            {EXEMPLARS[c.id] && EXEMPLARS[c.id].tickers.length ? (
              <p class="examples">
                <span class="exlabel">{EXEMPLARS[c.id].label}</span>
                {EXEMPLARS[c.id].tickers.map((t, i) => (
                  <>{i > 0 ? <span class="dot"> · </span> : ""}<a href={`/c/${t}`}>{t}</a></>
                ))}
              </p>
            ) : null}
            {c.seeAlso && c.seeAlso.length ? (
              <p class="see">
                See also:{" "}
                {c.seeAlso.map((sid, i) => (
                  <>
                    {i > 0 ? ", " : ""}
                    <a href={`#${sid}`}>{conceptById[sid]?.term || sid}</a>
                  </>
                ))}
              </p>
            ) : null}
          </article>
        ))}
      </div>
    </section>
  ))}

  <section class="band closing">
    <div class="prose">
      <p>
        These are tools for thinking, not a checklist to total up. No single number decides anything,
        and the craft is in weighing one honest signal against another. The originals teach that craft
        better than any page can: Graham's <em>Intelligent Investor</em>, the Berkshire letters, and a
        long look at real businesses, like the ones in the <a href="/">catalog</a>, where each
        company page asks these questions in the order an owner would.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <style>
    .hero h1 { margin: 0 0 8px; }
    .dek { font-family: var(--serif); font-style: italic; font-size: clamp(17px, 2.6vw, 21px); line-height: 1.45; color: var(--ink-soft); margin: 0; max-width: 62ch; }

    .band { margin: 34px 0; }
    .band h2 { border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule-strong); padding-bottom: 6px; scroll-margin-top: 12px; }
    .sub { font-family: var(--serif); font-style: italic; color: var(--muted); margin: 10px 0 0; max-width: 66ch; }
    .prose p { font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.65; color: var(--ink-soft); margin: 12px 0 0; max-width: 68ch; }
    .prose b { font-weight: 650; color: var(--ink); }
    .prose i { font-style: italic; }
    .bridge { border-top: 1px solid var(--rule); border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule); padding: 18px 0; }

    .intro { margin-top: 26px; }
    .grpnav { display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 6px 8px; margin: 18px 0 0; }
    .grpnav a {
      font-family: var(--sans); font-size: 11.5px; letter-spacing: 0.03em;
      color: var(--muted); border: 1px solid var(--rule); padding: 4px 10px; border-radius: 2px;
    }
    .grpnav a:hover { color: var(--ink); border-color: var(--rule-strong); text-decoration: none; }

    .concepts { margin: 12px 0 0; }
    .concept { padding: 18px 0; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule); scroll-margin-top: 64px; }
    .concept h3 { font-family: var(--sans); font-size: 16px; font-weight: 700; letter-spacing: 0; margin: 0; color: var(--ink); }
    .concept h3 .anchor { color: var(--ink); }
    .concept h3 .anchor:hover { color: var(--accent); text-decoration: none; }
    .short { font-family: var(--serif); font-size: 16px; font-style: italic; line-height: 1.5; color: var(--ink-soft); margin: 7px 0 0; max-width: 74ch; }
    .cbody { font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.62; color: var(--ink-dim); margin: 9px 0 0; max-width: 76ch; }
    .formula {
      font-family: var(--sans); font-size: 13px; color: var(--ink); margin: 10px 0 0;
      background: var(--accent-tint); border-left: 2px solid var(--accent); padding: 7px 12px;
      max-width: 74ch; font-variant-numeric: tabular-nums;
    }
    .flabel { display: block; font-size: 10.5px; letter-spacing: 0.07em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--muted); margin-bottom: 2px; }
    .forms { list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 12px 0 0; }
    .forms .formsHead { font-family: var(--sans); font-size: 10.5px; font-weight: 700; letter-spacing: 0.06em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--accent); margin-bottom: 6px; }
    .forms li { font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.55; color: var(--ink-dim); padding: 5px 0; border-top: 1px solid var(--rule); max-width: 78ch; }
    .forms li.formsHead { border-top: 0; padding: 0; }
    .formKind { font-weight: 600; color: var(--ink); }
    .examples { font-size: 13.5px; margin: 10px 0 0; display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; align-items: baseline; gap: 4px 7px; }
    .examples .exlabel { font-family: var(--sans); font-size: 10.5px; font-weight: 700; letter-spacing: 0.06em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--accent); margin-right: 3px; }
    .examples a { font-family: var(--sans); font-weight: 600; color: var(--ink); }
    .examples a:hover { color: var(--accent); }
    .examples .dot { color: var(--faint); }
    .see { font-size: 13px; color: var(--muted); margin: 9px 0 0; }

    @media (max-width: 520px) {
      .cbody, .short { max-width: none; }
    }
  </style>
</BaseLayout>
